"Keiler M., Knight J., Harrison S.","Climate change and geomorphological hazards in the eastern European Alps",2010,"Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences","368","1919",,"2461","2479",,,10.1098/rsta.2010.0047,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953009875&partnerID=40&md5=a81fb659d76c1fcc774983d2a0ca606a","Department of Geography and Regional Research, University of Vienna, Universitätsstraße 7, 1010 Vienna, Austria; Department of Geography, University of Exeter, Cornwall Campus, Penryn, TR10 9EZ, United Kingdom; Duke University, Division of Earth and Ocean Sciences, Durham, NC 27708, United States","Keiler, M., Department of Geography and Regional Research, University of Vienna, Universitätsstraße 7, 1010 Vienna, Austria, Duke University, Division of Earth and Ocean Sciences, Durham, NC 27708, United States; Knight, J., Department of Geography, University of Exeter, Cornwall Campus, Penryn, TR10 9EZ, United Kingdom; Harrison, S., Department of Geography, University of Exeter, Cornwall Campus, Penryn, TR10 9EZ, United Kingdom","Climate and environmental changes associated with anthropogenic global warming are being increasingly identified in the European Alps, as seen by changes in long-term high- alpine temperature, precipitation, glacier cover and permafrost. In turn, these changes impact on land-surface stability, and lead to increased frequency and magnitude of natural mountain hazards, including rock falls, debris flows, landslides, avalanches and floods. These hazards also impact on infrastructure, and socio-economic and cultural activities in mountain regions. This paper presents two case studies (2003 heatwave, 2005 floods) that demonstrate some of the interlinkages between physical processes and human activity in climatically sensitive alpine regions that are responding to ongoing climate change. Based on this evidence, we outline future implications of climate change on mountain environments and its impact on hazards and hazard management in paraglacial mountain systems. ©2010 The Royal Society.","Climate change; Hazards; Paraglacial; Risk management","Alpine regions; Anthropogenic global warming; Debris flows; Environmental change; European Alps; Hazard management; Human activities; Interlinkages; Mountain hazard; Mountain regions; Paraglacial; Physical process; Rockfalls; Socio-economics; Surface stability; Debris; Floods; Forestry; Global warming; Risk management; Rock bursts; Landforms",,,,,,"(2007) Climate Change in the European Alps. Adapting Winter Tourism, and Natural Hazards Managemen, , Agrawala, S. (ed.), Paris, France: OECD; Alexander, D., (2000) Confronting Catastrophe, , Oxford, UK: Oxford University Press; Allan, R.P., Soden, B.J., Large discrepancy between observed and simulated precipitation trends in the ascending and descending branches of the tropical circulation (2007) Geophy. Res. Lett., 34, pp. L18705. , (doi:10.1029/2007GL031460); (2005) Starkregen- Und Hochwasserereignis August 2005 in Vorarlberg, , Amt der Vorarlberger Landesregierung. (eds), Vorarlberger Landesregierung, Bregenz; Auer, I., Bohm, R., Jurkovic, A., Orlik, A., Potzmann, R., Schoner, W., Ungersbock, M., Mercalli, L., A new instrumental precipitation dataset for the greater alpine region for the period 1800-2002 (2005) International Journal of Climatology, 25 (2), pp. 139-166. , DOI 10.1002/joc.1135; Auer, I., HISTALP-historical instrumental climatological surface time series of the greater Alpine region 1760-2003 (2007) Int. J. Climatol., 27, pp. 17-46. , (doi:10.1002/joc.1377); Baggi, S., Schweizer, J., Characteristics of wet-snow avalanche activity: 20 years of observations from a high alpine valley (Dischma, Switzerland) (2009) Nat. Haz., 50, pp. 97-108. , (doi:10.1007/s11069-008-9322-7); Ballantyne, C.K., A general model of paraglacial landscape response (2002) The Holocene, 12, pp. 371-376. , (doi:10.1191/0959683602hl553fa); Bartolinie, E., Claps